    \section*{Purpose}
    
        The purpose of this proposal is to request authorization to purchase the laboratory equipment for the study of the Brewster’s Angle.
        
    \section*{Summary}
    
        On March 17, 2016, Dr. Neven Simicevic assigned our team to conduct the study of Brewster’s Angle.
        
        Undergraduate students in Science and Engineering majors are given opportunity to study Brewster's Angle by providing Physics related classes. A rational understanding of the phenomenon can be develop by enrolling in the classes; however, an integrated knowledge of the phenomenon requires both a reasonable theoretical background and experience in doing the Brewster's Angle experiment. Hence, it is necessary for students to have experience with measuring Brewster’s Angle using appropriate equipment in order to gain more insight into the subject than either attending lectures exclusively or doing the experiment without adequate equipment.
        

    \section*{Introduction}
    
        We experience reflected light in our everyday life; and yet, it is still striking to most of us that under certain circumstances, an interface can have zero reflection, even though it reflects light in most of the cases. Specifically, if the interface is shine by a light source under certain incident angle, no reflection occurs. This angle is called Brewster's Angle and will be the subject of our study.
        
    \section*{Theory}
        
        According to Snell's law:
        \begin{equation} \label{snell}
            n_1 \sin \theta_1=n_2 \sin \theta_2
        \end{equation}
        Apply Snell's law to Brewster's Angle $\theta_p$:
        \begin{equation} \label{brewster-snell}
            n_1 \sin \theta_p=n_2 \sin \theta_2
        \end{equation}
        Since Brewster's Angle properties indicate that $\theta_p + \theta_2 = 90^\circ$, we conclude:
        \begin{equation} \label{brewster's angle}
            \tan \theta_p = \frac{n_2}{n_1}
        \end{equation}
        \begin{figure}[H]
            \centering
            \includegraphics[width=10cm]{optfig_snell}
            \caption{A visualization of Snell's law under Brewster's Angle. If the interface had been shined under an incident angle other than $\theta_p$, the incident angle would have been simply $\theta_1$\cite{pasco}.}
        \end{figure}
        
        
