    \section*{Proposed Tasks}
        \subsection*{Set Up}
            \begin{enumerate}
                \item Set up the Spectrophotometer; assemble laser diode, polarizers, and collimating splits.
                \item Put Spectrophotometer disk on "backward" position.
                \item Adjust the two polarizers.
                \item Adjust the square analyzing polarizer.
                \item Polarize the laser light at 45°.
                \item Zero the Brewster’s Angle base disk.
                \item Align the laser beam.
                \item Plug the Light into Channel A and the Rotary Motion Sensor into Channels 1 & 2 on the ScienceWorkshop 500 interface. Open the DataStudio file "Brewsters."
                
            \end{enumerate}
        \subsection*{Procedures}
            \begin{enumerate}
                \item Zero the angle for Rotatory Motion Angle.
                \item Turn out the room light. Click on START. Set angle to 85 degrees and rotate the Brewster disk to about 85. Rotate the first polarizer to be as high as possible without exceeding 90percent.
                \item Enter the angle into the table and record the light intensity under "Total Light" column.
                \item Remove the analyzing polarizer. Observe the intensity approaching the minimum and record data every 1 degree near the minimum.
                \item Click on "Fit" and choose the polynomial fit. The Brewster's angle is the angle at which the reflection is a minimum.
                
            \end{enumerate}
    \section*{Schedule}
        The experiment is conducted on March 24, 2016. A report will be submitted to Dr. Neven Simicevic one week after the experiment.
        
